Okay, here's a breakdown of the bill, section by section, starting with Sec. 70401, as requested.

**Sec. 70401. Enhancement of employer-provided child care credit.**

This section increases the credit employers can claim for providing child care to their employees. It raises the percentage of qualified child care expenditures taken into account from 25% to 40%, with a 50% rate for eligible small businesses. The maximum credit amount is also increased to $500,000 ($600,000 for eligible small businesses), and these amounts are subject to inflation adjustments after 2026. The bill also clarifies rules regarding third-party intermediaries and jointly owned child care facilities.

**Sec. 70402. Enhancement of adoption credit.**

This section modifies the adoption credit, making a portion of it refundable. Specifically, up to $5,000 of the credit will be treated as a credit allowed under Subpart C, making it refundable. It also adjusts inflation for the credit amounts, and clarifies rules regarding carryforwards.

**Sec. 70403. Recognizing Indian tribal governments for purposes of determining whether a child has special needs for purposes of the adoption credit.**

This section expands the definition of who can determine if a child has special needs for the adoption credit. It now includes Indian tribal governments alongside state agencies, simplifying the process for Native American families seeking to claim the credit. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70404. Enhancement of the dependent care assistance program.**

This section increases the limit on employer-provided dependent care assistance that employees can receive tax-free. The limit is raised from $5,000 to $7,500 for individuals and $2,500 to $3,750 for spouses. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70405. Enhancement of child and dependent care tax credit.**

This section modifies the calculation of the Child and Dependent Care Tax Credit, making it more generous for lower-income families. It adjusts the applicable percentage used to calculate the credit, reducing the income thresholds at which the credit begins to phase out. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70411. Tax credit for contributions of individuals to scholarship granting organizations.**

This section creates a new tax credit for individuals who contribute to scholarship granting organizations that provide scholarships to low-income students for elementary and secondary education. The credit is capped at $1,700 and is subject to state limitations. It also establishes requirements for these organizations and provides for reporting and enforcement.

**Sec. 70412. Exclusion for employer payments of student loans.**

This section makes the student loan repayment assistance program permanent. It allows employers to pay up to $10,000 per employee towards their student loans tax-free, and increases this amount to $20,000 after 2026, with inflation adjustments. This encourages employers to help employees manage student loan debt.

**Sec. 70413. Additional expenses treated as qualified higher education expenses for purposes of 529 accounts.**

This section expands the types of expenses that can be covered by 529 accounts. It now includes expenses like tutoring, standardized testing fees, and online educational materials for both higher education and elementary/secondary education. It also increases the annual contribution limit for 529 accounts.

**Sec. 70414. Certain postsecondary credentialing expenses treated as qualified higher education expenses for purposes of 529 accounts.**

This section further expands the use of 529 accounts by including qualified postsecondary credentialing expenses. This includes costs associated with obtaining certifications and licenses, as well as continuing education required to maintain those credentials. It defines "recognized postsecondary credential programs" and related terms.

**Sec. 70415. Modification of excise tax on investment income of certain private colleges and universities.**

This section modifies the excise tax on investment income for private colleges and universities. It adjusts the tax rates based on endowment size and introduces new rules regarding net investment income, including treatment of student loan interest and federally-subsidized royalty income. The goal is to encourage these institutions to use their endowments to benefit students.

**Sec. 70416. Expanding application of tax on excess compensation within tax-exempt organizations.**

This section expands the rules regarding the tax on excess compensation paid to executives of tax-exempt organizations. It removes a previous sunset provision, ensuring the tax applies to compensation paid after December 31, 2016. This aims to prevent excessive compensation within non-profit organizations.

**Sec. 70421. Permanent renewal and enhancement of opportunity zones.**

This section makes the Opportunity Zone program permanent and makes several changes. It extends the designation period, adjusts the criteria for designating zones, and modifies rules related to capital gains invested in Opportunity Zone funds. The goal is to incentivize investment in economically distressed communities.

**Sec. 70422. Permanent enhancement of low-income housing tax credit.**

This section permanently increases the Low-Income Housing Tax Credit (LIHTC) allocation for states. It raises the state housing credit ceiling and modifies rules related to tax-exempt bond financing. This aims to increase the supply of affordable housing.

**Sec. 70423. Permanent extension of new markets tax credit.**

This section permanently extends the New Markets Tax Credit (NMTC), which encourages investment in low-income communities. This provides continued incentives for businesses to locate and expand in underserved areas.

**Sec. 70424. Permanent and expanded reinstatement of partial deduction for charitable contributions of individuals who do not elect to itemize.**

This section makes the temporary deduction for charitable contributions permanent for those who do not itemize. It increases the deduction amount to $1,000 for single filers and $2,000 for married filing jointly.

**Sec. 70425. 0.5 percent floor on deduction of contributions made by individuals.**

This section introduces a new 0.5% floor on charitable contributions for individuals. This means that individuals can only deduct charitable contributions exceeding 0.5% of their contribution base. It also establishes rules for carrying forward excess contributions.

**Sec. 70426. 1-percent floor on deduction of charitable contributions made by corporations.**

This section introduces a 1% floor on charitable contributions for corporations. This means corporations can only deduct contributions exceeding 1% of their taxable income. It also establishes rules for carrying forward excess contributions.

**Sec. 70427. Permanent increase in limitation on cover over of tax on distilled spirits.**

This section permanently increases the limit on the amount of tax that can be covered over by the federal government to states for distilled spirits.

**Sec. 70428. Nonprofit community development activities in remote native villages.**

This section clarifies that certain community development activities in remote Native Alaskan villages are eligible for tax-exempt treatment. It aims to support economic development in these isolated communities.

**Sec. 70429. Adjustment of charitable deduction for certain expenses incurred in support of Native Alaskan subsistence whaling.**

This section increases the limit on the charitable deduction for expenses related to Native Alaskan subsistence whaling.

**Sec. 70430. Exception to percentage of completion method of accounting for certain residential construction contracts.**

This section modifies the rules regarding the percentage of completion method of accounting for residential construction contracts. It provides a more favorable accounting treatment for certain projects.

**Sec. 70431. Expansion of qualified small business stock gain exclusion.**

This section expands the exclusion for capital gains from the sale of qualified small business stock. It phases in a 100% exclusion over a 5-year period and increases the per-issuer limit.

**Sec. 70432. Repeal of revision to de minimis rules for third party network transactions.**

This section restores the previous rules regarding de minimis payments for third-party network transactions. It increases the reporting threshold, reducing the burden on small businesses.

**Sec. 70433. Increase in threshold for requiring information reporting with respect to certain payees.**

This section increases the threshold for requiring information reporting on payments to certain payees from $600 to $2,000.

**Sec. 70434. Treatment of certain qualified sound recording productions.**

This section extends tax benefits to qualified sound recording productions, aligning them with the treatment of film and live theatrical productions.

**Sec. 70435. Exclusion of interest on loans secured by rural or agricultural real property.**

This section provides a tax exclusion for interest income on loans secured by rural or agricultural real property.

**Sec. 70436. Reduction of transfer and manufacturing taxes for certain devices.**

This section reduces the transfer and manufacturing taxes on certain devices.

**Sec. 70437. Treatment of capital gains from the sale of certain farmland property.**

This section provides a special tax treatment for capital gains from the sale of qualified farmland property to qualified farmers, allowing for installment payments.

**Sec. 70438. Extension of rules for treatment of certain disaster-related personal casualty losses.**

This section extends the rules for treating certain disaster-related personal casualty losses.

**Sec. 70439. Restoration of taxable REIT subsidiary asset test.**

This section restores the asset test for taxable REIT subsidiaries.
